"id": "archetype-a2-summit-logistics-wealth-change",
"problem_text": "Summit Logistics is an all-equity firm with 10 million shares outstanding. The firm is considering a financed project that will change the distribution of future asset values and require issuing new equity to outside investors. You are asked to compute the wealth change for old shareholders and interpret whether this is an example of debt overhang or a clean multi-state financing problem.",
"archetype": "A2-MultiStateProjectAndFinancing",
"solution_steps": [
{
"part": "A",
"prompt": "How do I know this is an A2 / multi-state project & financing problem?",
"reasoning": "The stem mentions: (1) multiple states of the world with different asset values, (2) probabilities for each state, (3) issuing new equity to outside investors for cash, and (4) computing wealth change for old shareholders. That combination—states + financing + old vs new shareholders—is exactly the A2 multi-state project & financing template, often with debt overhang as a special case if there is outstanding debt.",
"calculation": "Archetype triggers:\n- States of the world: asset values in 4 states (e.g., 200, 260, 320, 380).\n- Probabilities: equal probabilities 0.25 in each state.\n- Financing: new equity issued for cash today.\n- Question: wealth change for old shareholders.\n=> Tag as A2: Multi-State Project & Financing (possible A2A: Debt Overhang if there is debt).",
"sanity_check": "If the question is asking about: (i) old vs new shareholders, (ii) wealth change, and (iii) probability-weighted state payoffs with financing, there is almost always a state table and a k = Cash_raised / V_equity_post step somewhere in the solution."
},
{
"part": "B",
"prompt": "What information do I need? What’s given and what’s missing?",
"reasoning": "The question asks for wealth change to old shareholders. To compute that, I need the value of what they own before the transaction and after the transaction.\nBefore: value of existing equity.\nAfter: fraction of the post-issue equity they still own * post-issue equity value.\nTo find post-issue equity value, I need the project’s effect on asset values and the financing terms (how much cash comes in, what fraction is sold).",
"calculation": "Key objects:\n1. Asset value without project: V_assets,old in each state.\n2. Project payoff in each state (ΔV_project).\n3. New asset values with project: V_assets,new = V_assets,old + ΔV_project.\n4. Cash raised today: C_raise.\n5. Post-issue equity value (today): V_E,post = PV_t0(E[ V_assets,new_one_year ]) + C_raise.\n6. Fraction sold to new investors: k = C_raise / V_E,post.\n7. Wealth of old shareholders:\n   - Before: W_old,before = V_E,old.\n   - After: W_old,after = (1 - k) * V_E,post.\n8. Wealth change: ΔW_old = W_old,after - W_old,before.",
"sanity_check": "Any time there are old vs new shareholders, you should explicitly write both W_old,before and W_old,after as today-values and then take the difference. Do NOT mix state-contingent one-year values and today’s values in the same line."
},
{
"part": "C",
"prompt": "What’s my approach if I don’t remember a formula for wealth change?",
"reasoning": "Instead of memorizing a formula, I rely on balance sheet logic and add–subtract reasoning. The new shareholders contribute cash; everyone (old+new) gets a share of the enlarged equity pie. The total equity pie is: PV of the new asset values plus the incoming cash. The new investors’ share is set by k = Cash_raised / V_E,post. Old shareholders get the residual fraction (1 - k). Compare what they keep to what they had before.",
"calculation": "Step 1: Compute the current value of assets (without project) as a one-year risky asset.\n- Suppose asset payoffs in one year are:\n  State 1: 200\n  State 2: 260\n  State 3: 320\n  State 4: 380\n- Probabilities: each 0.25; discount rate r_A = 10%.\nE[V_assets,old,1] = 0.25*(200 + 260 + 320 + 380) = 290.\nV_assets,old,0 = 290 / (1 + 0.10) = 263.64.\nWith 10M shares, pre-issue price per share = 263.64 / 10M = 26.36.\nSo V_E,old = 263.64.\n\nStep 2: Add the project to get new asset values.\n- Suppose the project adds {+20, +20, +20, +20} in each state at t=1.\nThen new asset payoffs:\n  220, 280, 340, 400 (still equal probability).\nE[V_assets,new,1] = 0.25*(220 + 280 + 340 + 400) = 310.\nV_assets,new,0 = 310 / 1.10 = 281.82.\n\nStep 3: Incorporate financing.\n- Suppose the firm raises C_raise = 30 at t=0 by issuing new equity.\nEquity value after: V_E,post = V_assets,new,0 + C_raise = 281.82 + 30 = 311.82.\nFraction sold to new investors: k = 30 / 311.82 ≈ 0.0962 (9.62%).",
"sanity_check": "Post-issue equity value should exceed both the pre-issue equity value and the amount raised, as long as the project has positive NPV. If your V_E,post is smaller than V_E,old, something is wrong with your project arithmetic or discounting."
},
{
"part": "D",
"prompt": "Build the state table and connect old vs new shareholders’ claims.",
"reasoning": "The state table is where I keep myself honest. It forces me to reconcile assets, debt (if any), equity, and fractions of equity in each state. For a pure equity firm, equity is just the residual claim on assets. After the issue, old and new equity together must sum to the total equity value in each state.",
"calculation": "One-year payoffs (after project):\n\nState 1: V_assets,new,1 = 220\nState 2: V_assets,new,1 = 280\nState 3: V_assets,new,1 = 340\nState 4: V_assets,new,1 = 400\n\nDiscounted values at t=0:\nV_assets,new,0 = 281.82 (computed above).\n\nTotal equity at t=0 is V_E,post = 311.82 (assets + 30 cash from new investors).\n\nOwnership:\n- New shareholders’ claim today: C_raise = 30.\n- Fraction k = 30 / 311.82.\n- Old shareholders’ claim today: 311.82 - 30 = 281.82 = V_assets,new,0.\n\nInterpretation: old shareholders keep all the asset value but give up a fraction k of it, because k of equity is owned by new investors. The state table makes it easy to see that all we are really doing is slicing the equity pie.",
"sanity_check": "In any state, the value of assets must equal the total value of all claims (debt + preferred + common). For a pure equity firm, assets = total equity = equity_old + equity_new in each state. If your state table violates basic balance sheet identity, fix that first."
},
{
"part": "E",
"prompt": "Compute wealth change for old shareholders and interpret the result.",
"reasoning": "Now that I have pre- and post-transaction values, I just compare. The key is to compare today-values, not one-year payoffs, and be clear about whose wealth I’m measuring (old shareholders only).",
"calculation": "Wealth of old shareholders:\n- Before: W_old,before = V_E,old = 263.64.\n- After: W_old,after = (1 - k) * V_E,post.\n  = (1 - 0.0962) * 311.82 ≈ 0.9038 * 311.82 ≈ 281.82.\n\nWealth change:\nΔW_old = 281.82 - 263.64 = +18.18.\n\nInterpretation:\n- The project increases asset value by 18.18 (NPV_project = 281.82 - 263.64).\n- Old shareholders end up capturing that entire NPV here because the new equity issue is fairly priced at 30 (they give away C_raise = 30 and receive equity worth 30 in return).",
"sanity_check": "If the equity issue is correctly priced and there is no debt, then ΔW_old should equal the project NPV. If you find old shareholders gaining or losing more than the project NPV, the equity issue is mispriced or you’ve double-counted the cash raised."
},
{
"part": "F",
"prompt": "Connect to debt overhang / agency logic when there IS debt.",
"reasoning": "The Summit Logistics pattern is often used to illustrate debt overhang: situations where a positive NPV project is rejected because most of the benefit goes to existing debt holders, not equity. The mechanics are the same, but the asset payoff table now includes debt contracts and priority. Equity may refuse to issue new equity if the financing is zero NPV for them but positive NPV for creditors.",
"calculation": "Debt overhang logic (generic):\n1. Compute project NPV at the asset level: NPV_project > 0.\n2. Add debt to the state table with absolute priority:\n   - Debt gets min(promised, assets) in each state.\n   - Equity gets residual = assets - debt cash flow.\n3. Re-compute equity value with and without the project.\n4. If ΔV_equity < 0 even though NPV_project > 0, equity holders will block the project (debt overhang). \n5. If equity also has to *issue* new equity to finance the project, you then layer in the A2 financing logic (k, C_raise, etc.) on top of the priority structure.",
"sanity_check": "In a classic A2A (Debt Overhang) question, you should see: (1) outstanding risky debt, (2) a positive NPV project, (3) a decision that depends on whether the old equity is willing to issue new equity or invest inside. If debtholders capture most of the project’s value, equity will rationally refuse the project."
}
],
"key_insights": [
"Multi-state project & financing problems always boil down to: (1) compute asset value with and without the project, (2) figure out who owns which slice of the equity pie before and after financing, and (3) compare old shareholders’ wealth.",
"The fraction sold to new equity investors is not arbitrary: k = Cash_raised / V_E,post. This ensures the equity issue is zero-NPV given the market’s beliefs.",
"When there is no debt and the equity issue is correctly priced, old shareholders’ wealth change equals the project NPV.",
"Debt overhang arises when there is outstanding risky debt: positive NPV projects can be blocked because much of the benefit accrues to debtholders, not equity."
],
"common_mistakes": [
"Using promised returns (like 9.4%) instead of expected returns when discounting risky multi-state payoffs.",
"Computing k = Cash_raised / V_assets,new,0 instead of k = Cash_raised / V_E,post (you must include the cash raised itself in the post-issue equity value).",
"Comparing a one-year equity payoff after the project to a today-value of equity before the project. All wealth comparisons must be in the same time units.",
"Ignoring the financing leg and assuming old shareholders automatically capture the full project NPV, even when they sell a large fraction of the firm to new investors."
]
